---
name: order-analysis
description: Classify court order PDFs using ML rule-based analysis with optional LLM fallback, then persist the analysis result and update the case lifecycle status.
tags: [backend, ml, analysis, classification, llm, firestore]
---

## Overview

Order analysis takes a downloaded court order PDF and produces a structured classification result. The primary path is a deterministic rule-based classifier (`order_analyzer.py`). When confidence is below threshold and LLM fallback is enabled, `ml_enhanced_parser.py` delegates to `llm_extractor.py` (Ollama or Firecrawl). Results are stored in the `order-analysis` collection and the case lifecycle is advanced to `analysed`.

## Key Files

- `billingonaire_backend/order_analyzer.py` — deterministic rule-based classification
- `billingonaire_backend/ml_enhanced_parser.py` — LLM-enhanced parser orchestrating fallback
- `billingonaire_backend/llm_extractor.py` — Ollama / Firecrawl LLM extraction integration
- `billingonaire_backend/main.py` — `/analyze-order`, `/analysis-history`, `/analysis-stats`, `/jobs/analyze-orders`, `/auto-orders/analyze-case/{id}`
- `billingonaire_backend/specs/features/order_analysis.feature` — acceptance scenarios
- `billingonaire_backend/specs/steps/order_analysis_steps.py` — step implementations

## Firestore Collections Used

| Collection | Operation | Key Fields |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| `order-analysis` | write | `case_ref`, `analysis_category`, `category_confidence`, `order_date`, `fallback_used`, `fallback_diagnostics` |
| `case-details` | write | `lifecycle_status` → `analysed` or `analyse_failed` |

## Analysis Categories

| Category | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `ADJOURNED` | Matter adjourned without substantive hearing |
| `HEARD_AND_ADJOURNED` | Matter heard and adjourned to a future date |
| `DISPOSED_OFF` | Petition dismissed or otherwise finally disposed |
| `ALLOWED` | Petition/application allowed by court |
| `PART_HEARD` | Matter partially heard; will continue |

## LLM Fallback Configuration

The LLM fallback is **opt-in** and controlled entirely through environment variables:

| Variable | Default | Effect |
|----------|---------|--------|
| `ORDER_ENABLE_LLM_FALLBACK` | `false` | Master switch for LLM fallback |
| `ORDER_LLM_FALLBACK_MIN_CATEGORY_CONFIDENCE` | `0.6` | Skip fallback if rule-based confidence ≥ this |
| `ORDER_LLM_FALLBACK_MIN_QUALITY` | `0.5` | Minimum quality to accept an LLM result |
| `ORDER_LLM_FALLBACK_MIN_CASES` | `1` | Minimum case count to attempt fallback |
| `ORDER_LLM_PROVIDER` | `ollama` | LLM provider identifier |
| `ORDER_LLM_MODEL` | model name | LLM model to invoke |
| `OLLAMA_BASE_URL` | — | Ollama service URL |
| `ORDER_LLM_TIMEOUT_SECONDS` | `30` | Per-request timeout for LLM calls |

## API Endpoints

| Endpoint | Method | Auth | Description |
|----------|--------|------|-------------|
| `/analyze-order` | POST | Yes | Classify a court order PDF |
| `/analysis-history` | GET | Yes | Past analysis records for a `case_ref` |
| `/analysis-stats` | GET | Yes | Aggregate counts per `analysis_category` |
| `/jobs/analyze-orders` | POST | Yes | Background job: analyse all `fetch_succeeded` cases |
| `/auto-orders/analyze-case/{id}` | POST | Yes | Synchronously analyse one case by ID |

## Business Rules

- Deterministic extraction is always attempted first; LLM fallback is never primary path.
- An empty or corrupt PDF returns HTTP 400 with a descriptive error.
- `category_confidence` must be included in every response; ≥ 0.6 is considered reliable.
- When fallback is used, `fallback_used: true` and `fallback_diagnostics` are persisted for observability.
- A successful analysis advances the case to `analysed`; failure advances to `analyse_failed`.

## Implementation Pattern

When adding a new analysis category or extraction rule:

1. Add the new category constant and rule patterns to `order_analyzer.py`.
2. Ensure the new rule does not degrade confidence on already-classified categories — run existing unit tests.
3. Update `ml_enhanced_parser.py` prompt templates if the LLM fallback also needs to recognise the new category.
4. Add a Gherkin scenario to `specs/features/order_analysis.feature` covering the new category.
5. Write a unit test for the new rule in `tests/unit/`.

## Example Analysis Response Shape

```json
{
  "case_ref": "WP/3373/2024",
  "analysis_category": "HEARD_AND_ADJOURNED",
  "category_confidence": 0.87,
  "order_date": "01/10/2024",
  "fallback_used": false,
  "fallback_diagnostics": null
}
```
